00:00:11.745 --> 00:00:13.120
JONATHAN GRUBER:
All right, let's

00:00:13.120 --> 00:00:16.570
get started today with our
lecture on factor markets.

00:00:20.230 --> 00:00:24.010
So when we talked
about producer theory,

00:00:24.010 --> 00:00:27.670
we talked about input
prices, that firms

00:00:27.670 --> 00:00:30.432
had prices for their
wages and their capital.

00:00:30.432 --> 00:00:32.140
And we just sort of
posed those as given.

00:00:32.140 --> 00:00:33.932
I just sort of gave
you values for the wage

00:00:33.932 --> 00:00:35.430
and the renter rate of capital.

00:00:35.430 --> 00:00:38.360
But we never really talked about
where those prices come from.

00:00:38.360 --> 00:00:40.360
Given that they may be
the most important prices

00:00:40.360 --> 00:00:42.400
in our whole economy,
it's probably worth

00:00:42.400 --> 00:00:44.680
spending a little time
on talking about where

00:00:44.680 --> 00:00:46.780
do w and r actually come from.

00:00:46.780 --> 00:00:49.030
And that's we'll do for
the next three lectures,

00:00:49.030 --> 00:00:52.270
is talk about factor markets,
talk about the markets

00:00:52.270 --> 00:00:56.860
that give us the price
of labor and capital.

00:00:56.860 --> 00:00:59.440
We're going to start
by talking about factor

00:00:59.440 --> 00:01:04.065
demand, the general demand
for labor and capital.

00:01:04.065 --> 00:01:06.190
And then we'll move on to
talk about factor supply,

00:01:06.190 --> 00:01:07.852
where does supply come from.

00:01:07.852 --> 00:01:09.310
We'll then develop
the equilibrium,

00:01:09.310 --> 00:01:12.790
and that will tell us where
wages and the interest rate

00:01:12.790 --> 00:01:13.892
come from.

00:01:13.892 --> 00:01:15.850
So that's sort of the
map of where we're going,

00:01:15.850 --> 00:01:17.980
is we're basically
going to develop

00:01:17.980 --> 00:01:21.490
the markets that give us the
wage rate and the interest

00:01:21.490 --> 00:01:22.490
rate.

00:01:22.490 --> 00:01:29.060
So let's start with factor
demand, factor demand.

00:01:29.060 --> 00:01:32.450
And let's start, and
we're going to start

00:01:32.450 --> 00:01:33.728
with the cleanest case.

00:01:33.728 --> 00:01:36.020
We're going to assume that
factor markets are perfectly

00:01:36.020 --> 00:01:37.350
competitive.

00:01:37.350 --> 00:01:39.590
So unless I say
otherwise, we're assuming

00:01:39.590 --> 00:01:41.990
the market for
workers, or the market

00:01:41.990 --> 00:01:45.450
for machines, or capital,
is perfectly competitive.

00:01:45.450 --> 00:01:48.510
OK, we'll come back and bend
that a little bit later.

00:01:48.510 --> 00:01:51.770
So what that means is that
there's basically many sellers

00:01:51.770 --> 00:01:53.390
and buyers, OK?

00:01:53.390 --> 00:01:56.360
So any worker is
basically competing

00:01:56.360 --> 00:01:59.210
with lots of workers for jobs.

00:01:59.210 --> 00:02:01.160
Any firm is competing
with lots of firms

00:02:01.160 --> 00:02:04.913
to hire the workers, OK?

00:02:04.913 --> 00:02:05.830
And we're also going--

00:02:05.830 --> 00:02:08.610
we're going to assume a
perfectly competitive input

00:02:08.610 --> 00:02:12.310
market, that is lots
of firms and workers

00:02:12.310 --> 00:02:14.135
competing to match
with each other.

00:02:14.135 --> 00:02:16.510
We're also going to assume a
perfectly competitive output

00:02:16.510 --> 00:02:20.740
market, that is, we're going
to examine this for the case

00:02:20.740 --> 00:02:23.970
not of a monopoly firm but of
a perfectly competitive firm.

00:02:23.970 --> 00:02:26.470
So just think of this, you have
a perfectly competitive firm

00:02:26.470 --> 00:02:30.910
competing with lots of other
firms to hire workers, OK?

00:02:30.910 --> 00:02:34.180
So let's start by talking
about short run labor

00:02:34.180 --> 00:02:37.950
demand in this context.

00:02:37.950 --> 00:02:40.210
Let's talk about short
run labor demand.

00:02:40.210 --> 00:02:43.260
Now, in the short
run, capital is fixed.

00:02:43.260 --> 00:02:47.320
So our decision is just, do
we add another worker or not,

00:02:47.320 --> 00:02:48.750
or another hour of labor or not.

00:02:48.750 --> 00:02:50.850
Like I said, the units
don't really matter here,

00:02:50.850 --> 00:02:52.620
but let's take in
terms of workers.

00:02:52.620 --> 00:02:56.500
Do we add another worker or not?

00:02:56.500 --> 00:02:58.843
Well, as with everything
else in this course,

00:02:58.843 --> 00:03:01.510
we want to consider the marginal
benefits and the marginal costs

00:03:01.510 --> 00:03:03.580
of that decision.

00:03:03.580 --> 00:03:09.230
The marginal benefit
of an extra worker

00:03:09.230 --> 00:03:13.580
is that one extra unit of
labor raises productivity

00:03:13.580 --> 00:03:16.760
by the marginal
product of labor, OK?

00:03:16.760 --> 00:03:19.910
One more unit of labor
raises our output

00:03:19.910 --> 00:03:24.200
by the marginal
product of labor, OK?

00:03:24.200 --> 00:03:26.660
But that's not the only
part of the benefit,

00:03:26.660 --> 00:03:28.900
because we don't actually
care as a firm about units

00:03:28.900 --> 00:03:29.720
of output.

00:03:29.720 --> 00:03:32.700
We care about revenues.

00:03:32.700 --> 00:03:37.320
So the benefit of a worker is
not just the how many units

00:03:37.320 --> 00:03:41.580
it produces, but the
value of those units.

00:03:41.580 --> 00:03:44.700
And what is the value of
the next unit produced?

00:03:44.700 --> 00:03:47.760
It's the marginal revenue.

00:03:47.760 --> 00:03:50.270
So the value of the
next unit of labor

00:03:50.270 --> 00:03:55.635
is what we call the marginal
revenue product, MRP sub

00:03:55.635 --> 00:03:57.530
L. The marginal
revenue product is

00:03:57.530 --> 00:04:02.340
the marginal product of
labor times marginal revenue.

00:04:02.340 --> 00:04:05.430
That's the benefit of
another unit of labor.

00:04:05.430 --> 00:04:09.340
It's not just what they
make, but what it's worth.

00:04:09.340 --> 00:04:14.860
It's not just what they make,
but what it's worth, OK?

00:04:14.860 --> 00:04:16.833
So that's the marginal benefit.

00:04:16.833 --> 00:04:18.250
The value of another
unit of labor

00:04:18.250 --> 00:04:22.130
is it makes marginal revenue
product amount more stuff,

00:04:22.130 --> 00:04:25.233
and you sell that at
the marginal revenue.

00:04:25.233 --> 00:04:26.400
That's the marginal benefit.

00:04:26.400 --> 00:04:29.035
What's the marginal cost
of another unit of labor?

00:04:29.035 --> 00:04:31.410
So this is the marginal benefit
of another unit of labor.

00:04:31.410 --> 00:04:33.610
What's the marginal cost?

00:04:33.610 --> 00:04:36.500
Well, the marginal cost
of labor is just the wage.

00:04:36.500 --> 00:04:39.730
So we simply set this
equal to the wage.

00:04:39.730 --> 00:04:41.920
We set the marginal
revenue product of labor

00:04:41.920 --> 00:04:45.670
equal to the wage, and that
gives us our optimization

00:04:45.670 --> 00:04:48.930
condition for the
optimal amount of labor

00:04:48.930 --> 00:04:51.040
the firms want to demand--

00:04:51.040 --> 00:04:53.980
is to set the marginal
revenue product of labor

00:04:53.980 --> 00:04:54.880
equal to the wage.

00:04:57.660 --> 00:04:59.850
Marginal benefits of hiring
another unit of labor

00:04:59.850 --> 00:05:03.010
equals the marginal cost of
hiring of the unit of labor.

00:05:03.010 --> 00:05:05.920
Now to go further,
remember, I said

00:05:05.920 --> 00:05:08.273
this is a perfectly
competitive output market.

00:05:08.273 --> 00:05:10.690
So what is the marginal revenue
in a perfectly competitive

00:05:10.690 --> 00:05:12.510
output market?

00:05:12.510 --> 00:05:14.910
What's the marginal revenue
of a firm producing-- yeah.

00:05:14.910 --> 00:05:15.600
Price.

00:05:15.600 --> 00:05:18.540
So I can write this
more to say that I

00:05:18.540 --> 00:05:22.140
want to set the marginal product
of labor times the price equal

00:05:22.140 --> 00:05:26.380
to the wage, OK?

00:05:26.380 --> 00:05:28.450
So basically, what
we're saying here--

00:05:28.450 --> 00:05:32.800
think about it-- is hire workers
until the cost of the next unit

00:05:32.800 --> 00:05:36.430
of labor is the same as
what that unit will actually

00:05:36.430 --> 00:05:38.700
produce for you, OK?

00:05:38.700 --> 00:05:41.190
The next unit of
labor costs you w.

00:05:41.190 --> 00:05:43.680
It produces for you MPL times p.

00:05:43.680 --> 00:05:45.990
So you want to hire workers
until that condition is

00:05:45.990 --> 00:05:47.820
met, OK?

00:05:47.820 --> 00:05:53.640
So think about that, and figure
15-1 sort of shows this, OK?

00:05:53.640 --> 00:05:57.410
We have a supply of labor.

00:05:57.410 --> 00:05:59.790
In 15-1, that's
horizontal, because we're

00:05:59.790 --> 00:06:03.462
assuming competitive
market for workers, OK?

00:06:03.462 --> 00:06:04.920
We're assuming a
competitive market

00:06:04.920 --> 00:06:08.200
for workers, that is a
perfectly competitive market.

00:06:08.200 --> 00:06:11.550
So if I try to pay workers one
penny more than other firms,

00:06:11.550 --> 00:06:14.100
every worker in the world
will want to work for me.

00:06:14.100 --> 00:06:16.920
If I pay workers one penny
less than other firms,

00:06:16.920 --> 00:06:19.140
no workers will
want to work for me.

00:06:19.140 --> 00:06:21.270
That's what a perfectly
competitive labor market

00:06:21.270 --> 00:06:25.590
means, that literally, I am
a price taker in the input

00:06:25.590 --> 00:06:26.820
market.

00:06:26.820 --> 00:06:29.510
I don't get to set the wage, OK?

00:06:29.510 --> 00:06:31.740
I don't get to set the wage.

00:06:31.740 --> 00:06:35.890
The wage is given to
me by the labor market.

00:06:35.890 --> 00:06:38.222
So just like a perfectly
competitive firm

00:06:38.222 --> 00:06:40.180
doesn't get to set the
price of their product--

00:06:40.180 --> 00:06:42.660
it's given to them by
the competitive market.

00:06:42.660 --> 00:06:44.970
A perfectly competitive
firm in the input market

00:06:44.970 --> 00:06:47.220
doesn't get to set
the wage they pay.

00:06:47.220 --> 00:06:49.230
It's given them through
the kind of process

00:06:49.230 --> 00:06:53.580
that delivered us our prices
on the output side, OK?

00:06:53.580 --> 00:06:56.790
So we get a horizontal
labor supply curve.

00:06:56.790 --> 00:07:00.390
And then we have this downward
sloping labor demand curve.

00:07:00.390 --> 00:07:01.670
Why is it downward sloping?

00:07:01.670 --> 00:07:03.240
Someone raise their
hand and tell me.

00:07:03.240 --> 00:07:05.970
Why is the labor demand
curve downward sloping?

00:07:08.610 --> 00:07:09.110
Yeah.

00:07:09.110 --> 00:07:11.470
AUDIENCE: Marginal product
of labor is diminishing.

00:07:11.470 --> 00:07:12.512
JONATHAN GRUBER: Exactly.

00:07:12.512 --> 00:07:14.740
The diminishing marginal
product of labor

00:07:14.740 --> 00:07:17.380
means you have a
downward sloping

00:07:17.380 --> 00:07:19.390
marginal benefit of labor.

00:07:19.390 --> 00:07:21.560
Each additional-- remember,
holding capital fixed

00:07:21.560 --> 00:07:23.380
is only one shovel.

00:07:23.380 --> 00:07:25.990
So each additional
worker add less and less

00:07:25.990 --> 00:07:28.630
to digging that hole, OK?

00:07:28.630 --> 00:07:30.100
So marginal product
is diminishing.

00:07:30.100 --> 00:07:32.830
Since p is a constant,
that doesn't really

00:07:32.830 --> 00:07:33.692
affect the slope.

00:07:33.692 --> 00:07:34.900
I mean, it affects the slope.

00:07:34.900 --> 00:07:37.030
It doesn't really
affect the sign.

00:07:37.030 --> 00:07:38.235
Doesn't affect the sign.

00:07:38.235 --> 00:07:40.485
It's diminishing because the
marginal product of labor

00:07:40.485 --> 00:07:41.780
is diminishing.

00:07:41.780 --> 00:07:46.530
So the equilibrium is
where they intersect.

00:07:46.530 --> 00:07:49.610
So the bottom line-- this
is complicated and new--

00:07:49.610 --> 00:07:52.760
the bottom line intuition
is to think about,

00:07:52.760 --> 00:07:56.840
as I decide whether to hire
one more hour of work--

00:07:56.840 --> 00:07:57.980
you've got a firm.

00:07:57.980 --> 00:07:59.730
You've got to decide,
do I want the worker

00:07:59.730 --> 00:08:00.790
to work one more hour?

00:08:00.790 --> 00:08:02.167
You do the tradeoff
of, what am I

00:08:02.167 --> 00:08:04.250
going to pay them for an
hour versus what are they

00:08:04.250 --> 00:08:05.840
going to get me for an hour.

00:08:05.840 --> 00:08:08.090
What they're going to get
me is their marginal product

00:08:08.090 --> 00:08:11.510
times the price, OK?

00:08:11.510 --> 00:08:13.920
Now, that--

00:08:13.920 --> 00:08:16.580
So in other words, the wage is
not just the marginal product.

00:08:16.580 --> 00:08:19.280
It's imagining if two workers
were equally productive.

00:08:19.280 --> 00:08:22.950
With one more hour of work,
they each make three more units.

00:08:22.950 --> 00:08:27.330
But let's say, in one case, a
unit is a computer chip, OK?

00:08:27.330 --> 00:08:31.700
In another case, a
unit is a potato chip.

00:08:31.700 --> 00:08:34.086
We clearly would not want to
pay the same wage to someone

00:08:34.086 --> 00:08:36.669
who produces three more computer
chips to someone who produces

00:08:36.669 --> 00:08:39.080
three more potato chips.

00:08:39.080 --> 00:08:40.790
We'd want to pay a
lot more to the person

00:08:40.790 --> 00:08:41.873
to do more computer chips.

00:08:41.873 --> 00:08:42.530
Why?

00:08:42.530 --> 00:08:44.070
Not because computers
are inherently valuable.

00:08:44.070 --> 00:08:45.945
In fact, potato chips
are much more delicious

00:08:45.945 --> 00:08:47.480
than computer chips.

00:08:47.480 --> 00:08:50.460
Because they sell
for a higher price.

00:08:50.460 --> 00:08:52.490
So therefore, you'd
want to pay more

00:08:52.490 --> 00:08:56.270
to the worker who produces more
units of a more valuable good.

00:08:56.270 --> 00:09:01.145
So let's think about
a sports example, OK?

00:09:01.145 --> 00:09:03.020
And I realize we're all
about baseball today,

00:09:03.020 --> 00:09:03.800
as we should be.

00:09:03.800 --> 00:09:04.880
Go, Red Sox.

00:09:04.880 --> 00:09:09.410
But let's focus on
basketball for a minute, OK?

00:09:09.410 --> 00:09:12.500
Now, imagine you're a owner of
a team in the NBA, the National

00:09:12.500 --> 00:09:14.180
Basketball
Association, and you're

00:09:14.180 --> 00:09:18.070
trying to decide how much
you pay one of your players.

00:09:18.070 --> 00:09:22.090
So basically, in that
case, your goal is to--

00:09:22.090 --> 00:09:23.800
your goal is wins.

00:09:23.800 --> 00:09:24.593
That's the goal.

00:09:24.593 --> 00:09:27.010
That's the profit you're trying
to maximize, is your wins.

00:09:27.010 --> 00:09:29.110
Let's say you're probably
trying to maximize

00:09:29.110 --> 00:09:31.300
your revenues from
ads and stuff,

00:09:31.300 --> 00:09:33.125
but assume that's
proportional to wins.

00:09:33.125 --> 00:09:34.750
OK, assume that
basically, the more you

00:09:34.750 --> 00:09:36.090
win, the more money you make.

00:09:36.090 --> 00:09:39.400
So let's say the thing you're
trying to maximize is wins, OK?

00:09:39.400 --> 00:09:41.680
So your labor demand,
the marginal product

00:09:41.680 --> 00:09:45.400
you care about, is the
contribution of the next player

00:09:45.400 --> 00:09:46.985
to your win total.

00:09:46.985 --> 00:09:48.110
That's what you care about.

00:09:48.110 --> 00:09:51.440
The marginal product of labor is
how much does that next player

00:09:51.440 --> 00:09:54.140
add to my win total, OK?

00:09:54.140 --> 00:09:57.248
So for example, LeBron James,
the best player in basketball,

00:09:57.248 --> 00:09:58.790
arguably the best
player in history--

00:09:58.790 --> 00:10:01.290
we could have that-- we could
have the LeBron versus Michael

00:10:01.290 --> 00:10:02.690
debate some other time, OK?

00:10:02.690 --> 00:10:07.100
LeBron James makes $31
million, and that's

00:10:07.100 --> 00:10:10.070
because his marginal
product is enormous.

00:10:10.070 --> 00:10:13.520
He adds a huge amount
of wins to any team, OK?

00:10:13.520 --> 00:10:14.395
We'll see with the--

00:10:14.395 --> 00:10:15.770
we'll run the
experiment to watch

00:10:15.770 --> 00:10:18.190
how the Cleveland Cavaliers
tank this year once LeBron

00:10:18.190 --> 00:10:20.730
has left, OK?

00:10:20.730 --> 00:10:22.860
Now, other players
don't make as much.

00:10:22.860 --> 00:10:25.530
Let's compare LeBron
James to Nate Robinson.

00:10:25.530 --> 00:10:27.570
You guys might not
know Nate Robinson is.

00:10:27.570 --> 00:10:30.420
He's one of the shortest players
in the history of the NBA

00:10:30.420 --> 00:10:33.960
at a paltry 5'9", which sounds
pretty tall to you and I,

00:10:33.960 --> 00:10:36.540
but it's tiny for the NBA.

00:10:36.540 --> 00:10:37.830
He was a very exciting player.

00:10:37.830 --> 00:10:39.030
It's kind of fun to
watch this little guy

00:10:39.030 --> 00:10:39.988
run among these giants.

00:10:42.690 --> 00:10:44.218
But he was just OK.

00:10:44.218 --> 00:10:45.260
He wasn't a great player.

00:10:45.260 --> 00:10:46.135
He was a fine player.

00:10:46.135 --> 00:10:50.160
He made about $2 million a
year by the end of his career.

00:10:50.160 --> 00:10:52.848
So basically, you have
LeBron making 31 million

00:10:52.848 --> 00:10:54.390
and Nate Robinson
making two million,

00:10:54.390 --> 00:10:56.598
and that's sort of related
to their marginal product.

00:10:56.598 --> 00:10:58.440
So LeBron adds a lot
more to your wins.

00:10:58.440 --> 00:11:00.362
Now, what happened
is Nate Robinson

00:11:00.362 --> 00:11:01.820
quit basketball in
the US, and went

00:11:01.820 --> 00:11:03.697
to play basketball in Israel.

00:11:03.697 --> 00:11:05.030
In Israel, they love basketball.

00:11:05.030 --> 00:11:05.540
They have a league.

00:11:05.540 --> 00:11:07.280
And he went to Israel,
and he was dominant.

00:11:07.280 --> 00:11:09.530
He was the best player in
Israel, because they don't--

00:11:09.530 --> 00:11:11.780
it's not as good as the US, OK?

00:11:11.780 --> 00:11:14.348
So his marginal
product went way up.

00:11:14.348 --> 00:11:15.890
Nate Robinson went
from being someone

00:11:15.890 --> 00:11:18.140
that had a small marginal
product to maybe the highest

